`WARNING: Duplicate declaration.` will be emitted without this code, since sphinx will believe the two `func()` below are the same when they are not at all.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
/** \brief some struct */
struct some_struct
{
	/** \brief stolen code, lvalue */
	void func() &
	{
		std::cout << "lvalue\n";
	}
	/** \brief stolen code, rvalue */
	void func() &&
	{
		std::cout << "rvalue\n";
	}
};
```

At first look, I think you want to persist `start_url` in next sub-requests. As noted, `make_requests_from_url` acts on the start urls, but `parse_page` receives responses from whatever requests your rules found, so these requests don't have the `start_url` meta value.

You could override the `CrawlSpider` internal methods, to persist the meta `start_url`, for example here: https://github.com/scrapy/scrapy/blob/1.1/scrapy/spiders/crawl.py#L51

Or you can persist the meta values in a spider middleware: http://doc.scrapy.org/en/latest/topics/spider-middleware.html#writing-your-own-spider-middleware

Something like:

```python
class MySpiderMiddleware(object):

    def process_spider_output(self, response, result, spider):
        for request_or_item in result:
            if isinstance(request_or_item, Request):
                self.persist_meta(response, request_or_item)
            yield request_or_item

    def persist_meta(self, response, request):
        # It is expected to all responses have a start_url meta value.
        request.meta['start_url'] = response.meta['start_url']

Can't you have a cache decorator wrap around what you have? So the cache decorator would be hit first and it would return the results if there's something in the cache. If not, the rate limit decorator would be hit that would check if there have been to many API calls.

I haven't tried it, but I'm using Django's `[cache_memoize](https://github.com/peterbe/django-cache-memoize)` and I think it could work like this:

```python
@cache_memoize(3600)
@ratelimit(1, 10)
def apiCall():
    return requests.get('http://example.com/api').text
```

